      "title": "See also"
    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "The probability mass function (PMF) for the binomial distribution is"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "formulas": [
            "P(N) = \\binom{n}{N}p^N(1-p)^{n-N},"
          ],
          "type": "math_block"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "where "
            },
            {
              "kind": "math",
              "latex": "n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " is the number of trials, "
            },
            {
              "kind": "math",
              "latex": "p"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " is the probability\nof success, and "
            },
            {
              "kind": "math",
              "latex": "N"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " is the number of successes."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "When estimating the standard error of a proportion in a population by\nusing a random sample, the normal distribution works well unless the\nproduct p*n <=5, where p = population proportion estimate, and n =\nnumber of samples, in which case the binomial distribution is used\ninstead. For example, a sample of 15 people shows 4 who are left\nhanded, and 11 who are right handed. Then p = 4/15 = 27%. 0.27*15 = 4,\nso the binomial distribution should be used in this case."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Notes"
    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "raw_kind": "footnote",
          "raw_text": "1\n\nDalgaard, Peter, \"Introductory Statistics with R\",\nSpringer-Verlag, 2002.",
          "type": "raw_block"
        },
        {
          "raw_kind": "footnote",
          "raw_text": "2\n\nGlantz, Stanton A. \"Primer of Biostatistics.\", McGraw-Hill,\nFifth Edition, 2002.",
          "type": "raw_block"
        },
        {
          "raw_kind": "footnote",
          "raw_text": "3\n\nLentner, Marvin, \"Elementary Applied Statistics\", Bogden\nand Quigley, 1972.",
          "type": "raw_block"
        },
        {
          "raw_kind": "footnote",
          "raw_text": "4\n\nWeisstein, Eric W. \"Binomial Distribution.\" From MathWorld--A\nWolfram Web Resource.\nhttps://mathworld.wolfram.com/BinomialDistribution.html",
          "type": "raw_block"
        },
        {
          "raw_kind": "footnote",
          "raw_text": "5\n\nWikipedia, \"Binomial distribution\",\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_distribution",
          "type": "raw_block"
        }
      ],
      "title": "References"
    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "Draw samples from the distribution:"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "lines": [
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "n, p = 10, .5  # number of trials, probability of each trial"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "s = fnp.random.binomial(n, p, 1000)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "# result of flipping a coin 10 times, tested 1000 times."
            }
          ],
          "type": "doctest_block"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "A real world example. A company drills 9 wild-cat oil exploration\nwells, each with an estimated probability of success of 0.1. All nine\nwells fail. What is the probability of that happening?"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "Let's do 20,000 trials of the model, and count the number that\ngenerate zero positive results."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "lines": [
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "sum(fnp.random.binomial(9, 0.1, 20000) == 0)/20000."
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "# answer = 0.38885, or 38%."
            }
          ],
          "type": "doctest_block"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Examples"
    }
  ],
